defaultClubs.name: Aikido at UHM
defaultClubs.description: The Aikido Club at UHM was founded by Robert Little Sensei (5th dan) and is affiliated with the Hawaii Aikido Federation. Little Sensei is the chief instructor of the club. Visitors are welcome and classes are always open to beginning students.

defaultClubs.name: Alohathon Dance Marathon
defaultClubs.description: "AlohaThon Dance Marathon at the University of Hawaiʻ at Mānoa is the Aloha State's first and only Miracle Network Dance Marathon (DM). It is a nationwide movement held at over 400 college campuses in support of Children's Miracle Network. In 2019, a total of over $44 million was raised from DMs across the nation. Since inception, Miracle Network Dance Marathon has raised more than $400 million for kids across North America- ensuring that no child or family fights pediatric illness or injury alone. Participants are challenged each year to raise funds that culminate up to the 6-hour long main virtual event. AlohaThon celebrates with non-stop dancing to fight for the keiki of Hawaiʻi. All funds raised are donated to our local Children's Miracle Network Hospital, Kapiolani Medical Center for Women & Children."

defaultClubs.name: C.O.P. Alaka'ina
defaultClubs.description:

defaultClubs.name: CTAHR Student Ambassadors

defaultClubs.name: Delta Sigma Pi: Rho Chi

defaultClubs.name: Disney Ohana Club

defaultClubs.name: Engineers' Council at the Univeristy of Hawaii
defaultClubs.description: The Engineers’ Council at the University of Hawaiʻi (ECUH) is a student-operated executive board, consisting of elected executive board (officer) positions, Affiliate College of Engineering (COE) Student Organization representatives, and a council member body. The mission of the ECUH is to provide unity action through cooperative, transparent, and effective representation of the student body of the COE at the University of Hawaiʻi at Mānoa. By collaborating with students, faculty, affiliate student organizations, affiliate project organizations, and professional partners, the ECUH serves to promote academic, intellectual, cultural, and social understanding throughout the COE, and to provide students with the finest education environment possible.

defaultClubs.name: Eta Kappa Nu

defaultClubs.name: Every Nation Campus at the University of Hawaii at Manoa
defaultClubs.description: Every Nation Campus Ministries partners with schools to help students excel in their academics, develop leadership skills, be a positive influence in their community, and pursue a Christ-centered life.

defaultClubs.name: Ēwe ‘Ula
defaultClubs.description:
Nurses are among the front-line health workers that provide the time and hands on care for their patients.  Native Hawaiian Health has improved over the years  yet health disparities continue to exist.  Among the disparities are the small number of Native Hawaiian nurses.  Many institutions of education and health repeat non-indigenous values and practices which contribute to indigenous mis-trust and care confusion.  Cultural knowledge and cultural safety can change this. 
Ēwe ʻUla was created to provide a place for Native Hawaiian Nurses, and Kākoʻo (Allies of Native Hawaiian Health and the work of Native Hawaiian Nurses), to nurture, gather, support, and mentor one another.  The group was founded on the principle that creating a positive cultural identity will help nurses to bridge the gap between Western Nursing Education, Health Care and indigenous values for the patients they care for.

defaultClubs.name: Family Medicine Interest Group
defaultClubs.description: The Family Medicine Interest Group (FMIG) is a medical student-run organization that is advised by the Faculty Advisor, Dr. Jill Omori.  FMIG provides unique opportunities for medical students to learn about Family Medicine and to be involved with the community.

defaultClubs.name: Food Science and Human Nutrition Council
defaultClubs.description: Share news and volunteer opportunities relating to General food and nutrition with attending students. Organized club for students in majors relating to food and nutrition or those who are interested.

defaultClubs.name: Formula SAE Rainbow Warrior Racing
defaultClubs.description: Formula SAE is an international competition, in which students from universities design a Formula One-style racecar. The Rainbow Warrior Racing (RWR) Team's objective this year is to improve on and advance the design of the electric Formula racecar from last year with the goal to attend the competition and represent the University of Hawai’i at Manoa. Our mission as an organization is to provide our members with experiences that no course can replace, and develop them as engineers and people. The RWR team is a part of a senior design course, but the organization is also open to underclassmen members, which will give them an opportunity to expand their knowledge and improve the program in future years.

defaultClubs.name: Graduate Hui Ola Pono

The Hui facilitates communication and involvement among students through scheduled meetings, coordination of social and educational activities, and dissemination of necessary information. The Hui is an organization that provides students with opportunities to promote Public Health within both the university and Hawaiʻi community at large through outreach, education, and fundraising. Another facet of the group is to provide support and guidance for incoming students and link students in the Public Health program with other students and Public Health professionals locally, nationally, and internationally.

defaultClubs.name: KRS Club

Phi Alpha Theta fosters a commitment to historical excellence and academic achievement.

defaultClubs.description: Primary Care Progress at UH strives to expand the primary care workforce in Hawai‘i by  promoting awareness, interdisciplinary collaboration, mentorship, community engagement,  and advocacy & leadership among students across various professional schools.

defaultClubs.name: Public Relations Student Society of America
defaultClubs.description: The Public Relations Student Society of America (PRSSA) strives to involve students in Hawai'i's communications industry through speaking events, career tours, networking mixers and more!

Red Cross Clubs empower you with knowledge and life-saving skills to help prepare your school and community to respond to emergencies.

defaultClubs.name: Reformed University Fellowship

We are a group on campus seeking to grow in our relationship with God while also sharing what we know to others. RUF is a community where students can make friends, grow in their faith, serve the community and have fun doing it.

Rural Health Interest Group

defaultClubs.name: Second Language Studies Student Association
defaultClubs.description: The Second Language Studies Student Association (SLSSA) is an association of the Graduate Students of the Second Language Studies Department at the University of Hawaiʻi at Mānoa. It is dedicated to developing the academic, professional and social identities of its members. It seeks to provide avenues for development of these identities for its members through various events throughout the year. It also seeks to connect them to the career and volunteer opportunities outside the department and University.

defaultClubs.name: Social Leaders at Manoa
defaultClubs.description: To cultivate a prestigious gathering of student leaders through passionate engagement and connection with the Dean of the College of Social Sciences

defaultClubs.name: Society of Automotive Engineers
defaultClubs.description: The mission of the SAE is to provide technical resources and facilitate the integration of underclassmen in environments that develop leadership, time management, and technical skills through our sponsored projects.

defaultClubs.name: Society of Human Resources Management - Aloha Chapter
defaultClubs.description: Promotes collaboration and interaction among diverse individuals with an expressed interest in the study of Human Resources Management and its theories, practices, and applications.

defaultClubs.name: Society of Women Engineers
defaultClubs.description: Empower women to achieve full potential in careers as engineers and leaders, expand the image of the engineering and technology professions as a positive force in improving the quality of life, and demonstrate the value of diversity and inclusion.

defaultClubs.name: Student Chapter of the American Society of Landscape Architects at UH Manoa
defaultClubs.description:
"The purpose of the Society is the advancement of knowledge, education, and skill in the art and science of landscape architecture as an instrument of service in the public welfare.  To this end, the Society promotes the profession of landscape architecture and advances the practice through advocacy, education, communication, and fellowship.

The purpose of the Chapter shall be to bring students together through organized activities that 1) are consistent with the purpose and policies of the Society; 2) enhance understanding of the Society, the profession, and related disciplines; 3) improve skills and knowledge and complement the educational curriculum; and 4) encourage participation in the programs and activities of the Society, its professional chapters, and student chapters. "

defaultClubs.name: Student Nurses' Association at UH Manoa
defaultClubs.description:
A. To assume responsibility for contributing to nursing education in order to provide for the highest quality of health care. B. To provide programs representative of fundamental interests and concerns to nursing students. C. To aid in th e development of the whole person, including his/her professional role, his/her responsibility for health care of people in all walks of life. 
(1) SNA members will work to create a positive, professional atmosphere, which will focus on mentorship, leadership, and collaboration. 
(2) To promote open communication and collaboration throughout the student body, faculty, and administration of the nursing program. 
(3) To select students as representatives to participate on school committees in order to share responsibility and accountability for governance within the nursing program. 
(4) SNA officers and class representatives will act as advocates for nursing students by effectively articulating the collective concerns of the student body through the established channels of communication at the Department of Nursing. 
(5) To foster and develop mentoring relationships among students by assisting new students in the school orientation program and offering ongoing assistance on a formal and/or informal basis. 
(6) To promote participation in all SNA/class activities and opportunities to develop leadership skills through various volunteer, social, educational, and fundraising activities. 
(7) To represent the students of the Department of Nursing (DON) in the pursuit of excellence in educational training toward competent, professional care and practice. 
(8) To facilitate student knowledge of and participation in professional nursing organizations. 
(9) To assist in increased public understanding of the role of the student and professional nurse beyond the clinical setting. 
(10) To seek and provide service opportunities for students that meet the health careneeds and wellbeing of community members regardless of race, ethnicity, gender, sexual orientation, socioeconomic status, age, physical abilities, political beliefs, religious beliefs, nationality, or other ideologies.

defaultClubs.name: Student Veterans of America at the University of Hawai’i at Mānoa
defaultClubs.description: SVA’s purpose is to establish ties with the community and school while empowering veterans to pursue their education during their transition from military life to civilian life at the University of Hawai’i at Mānoa.

defaultClubs.name: Supporting Women in Technology and Computing Hawaii
defaultClubs.description: To support women and minorities, promote gender and racial equality, facilitate professional, technical & personal development events, create an environment and atmosphere where women can feel safe, prevent violence against women by raising awareness of campus resources, and provide an overall sense of community.

defaultClubs.name: Tea Club at the University of Hawaii at Manoa
defaultClubs.description: To promote peacefulness from one bowl of tea, and enjoy the Japanese culture.

defaultClubs.name: The IMUA Scholarly Society at UH (Short name: IMUA Labs)
defaultClubs.description:
"The IMUA Scholarly Society (Society) is a knowledge-innovation and transformational-learning community open to all members of the University of Hawai‘i’s ‘Ohana and their community partners who are willing to collaborate to cultivate the collective intelligence and wisdom crucial for leading a dignified, fulfilling, and nature-respecting life in a rapidly changing and complex world. 

IMUA Labs is established to foster inclusive ecosocial innovation and transdisciplinary knowledge production for the benefit of all communities that call The Hawaiian Islands their home. The organization facilitates reflexive organizational learning within regional academic ecosystems aimed at generating intellectual capacity necessary for mounting effective responses to the grand challenges of socioecological transformation, energy transition, and climate change."

defaultClubs.name: The Navigators
defaultClubs.description: The Navigators is a group of college students seeking to know Christ, make him known, and help others do the same.

defaultClubs.name: The Pre-Veterinary Club at UH Manoa
defaultClubs.description: The Pre-Veterinary Club at the University of Hawaii at Manoa is committed to students who share an interest and passion for animals and veterinary medicine. The club accomplishes its mission by organizing events that emphasize education and hands-on experience. The club also participates in community service events.

defaultClubs.name: Timpuyog Organization
defaultClubs.description: We, the students of the Timpuyog Organization, believe in establishing a spirit of pride, emphasizing the advancement of the Ilokano language and culture, and providing opportunities for the meaningful exchanges of ideas.

defaultClubs.name: Travel Industry Management Student Association
defaultClubs.description: To foster the future leaders of Hawaii’s travel industry

defaultClubs.name: Unicef Unite Club
defaultClubs.description: The UNICEF UNITE Club at the University of Hawaii at Manoa represents UNICEF’s work by implementing UNICEF’s values—Care, Respect, Integrity, Trust, and Accountability—and core competencies that underline teamwork, communication, and determination. We are a team of committed advocates standing at a collegiate level who seek to bridge the gap between disadvantaged children and the rest of the world. We have continuously incorporated UNICEF’s values within the UHM community through various activities such as fundraisers, seminars, campaigns, and informative posts.

defaultClubs.name: VIP Team RoSE
defaultClubs.description: VIP Team RoSE has the goal to create a professional and safe atmosphere for students to collaborate on an engineering project that aims to design and fabricate a rover for the University Rover Challenge.

defaultClubs.name: Volunteers for Intercultural and Definitive Adventures (VIDA)
defaultClubs.description: VIDA is a non-profit organization that focuses on providing medical, dental, and veterinary healthcare to impoverished rural communities in Central America. VIDA Hawaii is Hawaii's first VIDA chapter at UH Manoa, and VIDA Hawaii aims to provide a service-learning experience to UH Manoa students who have an interest in the healthcare field and/or helping communities in need.
